B041C006V056	41	6	56	And wherever he entered, into villages, or cities, or country, they laid the sick in the streets, and begged him that they might even touch the fringe of his garment: and as many as touched him were made well.
B041C007V001	41	7	1	Then the Pharisees and some of the scribes, who came from Jerusalem, gathered around him.
B041C007V002	41	7	2	And when they saw some of his disciples eat bread with defiled, that is to say, with unwashed, hands, they found fault.
B041C007V003	41	7	3	(For the Pharisees, and all the Jews, do not eat unless they wash their hands, thus holding to the tradition of the elders.
B041C007V004	41	7	4	And when they come from the market, unless they wash, they do not eat. And there are many other traditions which they observe, such as the washing of cups, and pots, and vessels of copper.)
B041C007V005	41	7	5	Then the Pharisees and scribes asked him, Why do your disciples not walk according to the tradition of the elders, but rather eat bread with unwashed hands?
B041C007V006	41	7	6	He answered and said to them, Well has Isaiah prophesied of you hypocrites, as it is written, This people honours me with their lips, but their hearts are far from me.
B041C007V007	41	7	7	In vain do they worship me, teaching for doctrines the commandments of men.
B041C007V008	41	7	8	Laying aside the commandment of God, you hold to the traditions of men.
B041C007V009	41	7	9	And he said to them, You fully reject the commandment of God, that you may keep your own tradition.
B041C007V010	41	7	10	For Moses said, Honour your father and your mother; and, Whoever curses father or mother, let him be put to death:
B041C007V011	41	7	11	But you say, If a man shall say to his father or mother, whatever I have that might benefit you is Corban, that is to say, a gift to God,
B041C007V012	41	7	12	Then you do not allow him to do anything for his father or his mother;
B041C007V013	41	7	13	Thus making the word of God invalid through your tradition, which you have handed down: and you do many such things.
B041C007V014	41	7	14	And when he had called all the people to him, he said to them, Listen to me, every one of you, and understand:
B041C007V015	41	7	15	There is nothing from outside of a man that can defile him by entering into him: but the things which come out of him, those are the things that defile the man.
B041C007V016	41	7	16	[If any man has ears to hear, let him hear.]
B041C007V017	41	7	17	And when he entered into the house and left the people, his disciples asked him about the parable.
B041C007V018	41	7	18	And he said to them, Are you also without understanding? Do you not perceive, that whatever enters into the man from without, it cannot defile him;
B041C007V019	41	7	19	Because it does not enter into his heart, but into the belly, and is eliminated? Thus he declared all foods clean.
B041C007V020	41	7	20	And he said, That which comes out of the man, that defiles the man.
B041C007V021	41	7	21	For from within, out of the heart of men, proceed evil thoughts, sexual immorality, theft, murder, adultery,
B041C007V022	41	7	22	Covetousness, wickedness, deceit, lustfulness, envy, slander, pride, foolishness:
B041C007V023	41	7	23	All these evil things come from within, and defile the man.
B041C007V024	41	7	24	And from there he arose, and went into the regions of Tyre, and entered into a house, and would not have anyone know it: but he could not be hidden.
B041C007V025	41	7	25	But a certain woman, whose young daughter had an unclean spirit, heard of him, and came and fell at his feet:
B041C007V026	41	7	26	The woman was a Greek, a Syrophoenician by birth; and she begged him that he would cast forth the devil out of her daughter.
B041C007V027	41	7	27	But Jesus said to her, Let the children first be filled: for it is not right to take the children's bread, and to cast it to the dogs.
B041C007V028	41	7	28	And she answered and said to him, Yes, Lord: but even the dogs under the table eat the children's crumbs.
B041C007V029	41	7	29	And he said to her, For this answer go your way; the devil has gone out of your daughter.
B041C007V030	41	7	30	And when she came to her house, she found the devil gone, and her daughter lying upon the bed.
B041C007V031	41	7	31	And again, departing from the region of Tyre, through Sidon, he came to the sea of Galilee, in the region of Decapolis.
B041C007V032	41	7	32	And they brought to him one who was deaf, and had an impediment in his speech; and they begged him to put his hand upon him.
B041C007V033	41	7	33	And he took him aside from the multitude, and put his fingers into his ears, and he spit, and touched his tongue;
B041C007V034	41	7	34	And looking up to heaven, he sighed, and said to him, Ephphatha, that is, Be opened.
B041C007V035	41	7	35	And immediately his ears were opened, and the impediment of his tongue was loosened, and he spoke plainly.
B041C007V036	41	7	36	And he commanded them that they should tell no man: but the more he commanded them, the more widely they proclaimed it;
B041C007V037	41	7	37	And they were astonished beyond measure, saying, He has done all things well: he makes both the deaf to hear, and the dumb to speak.
B041C008V001	41	8	1	In those days another great multitude gathered, and as they had nothing to eat, Jesus called his disciples to him, and said to them,
B041C008V002	41	8	2	I have compassion on the multitude, because they have now been with me three days, and have nothing to eat:
B041C008V003	41	8	3	And if I send them away fasting to their own houses, they will faint on the way: for some of them came from afar.
B041C008V004	41	8	4	And his disciples answered him, Where can a man find enough bread to satisfy these men here in the wilderness?
B041C008V005	41	8	5	And he asked them, How many loaves do you have? And they said, Seven.
B041C008V006	41	8	6	And he commanded the people to sit down on the ground: and he took the seven loaves, and gave thanks, and broke them, and gave them to his disciples to set before them; and they set them before the people.
